[[File:Soga faminy tree.svg|thumb|right|337px|Simplified genealogy of the Soga clan]]
== Historical Analysis == The false accusations against Ishikawamaro highlight the internal divisions within the "Reform Government" of the Asuka period.<ref name="#1">Kuramoto Kazunobu, ''Soga Clan: The Rise and Fall of an Ancient Japanese Aristocracy'' (Chūō Kōron Shinsha, 2015)</ref> This government consisted of three factions: the non-Soga royal family, Crown Prince Naka no Ōe's allies, and the "Mahitsukimi" aristocracy led by the Left and Right Ministers.<ref name="#1"/> The introduction of a new Ranking system in 648, which excluded the traditional "purple caps" worn by the Left and Right Ministers, symbolized growing tensions between the royal authority and the ministers.<ref name="#1"/>
The death of {{ill|Abe no Uchimaro|ja|阿倍内麻呂|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe no Uchimaro|qq=|1=Abe no Uchimaro|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11657240}} (Left Minister) in 649, followed by Ishikawamaro’s forced suicide, signaled a shift in power dynamics. The appointments of {{ill|Kose no Tokuta|ja|巨勢徳太|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kose no Tokuta|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 巨勢徳多|1=Kose no Tokuta|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11479774}} and {{ill|Ōtomo no Nagatokuto|ja|大伴長徳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōtomo no Nagatokuto|qq=|1=Ōtomo no Nagatoko|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11432357}} as new ministers wearing "Great Purple Caps" further illustrate the restructuring of authority.<ref name="#1"/>
Himuka's involvement as Ishikawamaro's accuser and military commander underscores internal strife within the Soga clan. The Soga had been fracturing since the coup against {{ill|Prince Furubito no Ōe|ja|古人大兄皇子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prince Furubito no Ōe|qq=|1=Prince Furuhito-no-Ōe|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11410845}} in 645.<ref name="#1"/> Himuka’s actions likely reflect his attempt to secure power by leveraging royal favor, but his eventual disappearance from historical records suggests that he, too, became a pawn in Crown Prince Naka no Ōe's broader political strategy.<ref name="#1"/>
